      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "For a senior lab, looking for a balanced protein to fat ratio is smart; you don't want him shedding weight, but you also don't want him putting on extra pounds. A ratio where protein slightly exceeds fat, maybe something around **30-40% protein and 20-30% fat**, is often ideal. This provides the necessary muscle maintenance without being overly calorific, which is excellent for keeping a senior dog lean! Remember that portion control, no matter how good the food is, is just as important.\n\n!\n*The ratios are just suggestions, as much as the specific brand ingredients and the dog's individual metabolism play a role.*\n\n!\n*If your lab is more like a very large, very healthy, and slightly portly senior, you might lean towards the higher fat end for easier digestion, but usually, the slightly higher protein is the safer bet.*\n\n!\n*It’s always wise to consult your vet, who knows your lab's specific health needs best.*\n\n***\n\n(I've got to keep this to 2-5 sentences, I'll merge the advice!)\n\nFor your senior lab, aim for a protein that slightly outweighs the",
